  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a financial crime\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- International standards for anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Expanded global cooperation and information sharing\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Stricter reporting and monitoring mechanisms\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Expanded scrutiny of online financial transactions\n- Enhanced digital tracking and detection capabilities\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Enhanced international collaboration\n- Risk-based approach to AML compliance\n\n6. Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Suspicious activity reporting\n- Regular risk assessments\n- Complex transaction monitoring\n\nThese legislative developments reflect an ongoing effort to address increasingly sophisticated money laundering techniques.",
